<font color="#FF0000">GRATITUDE</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 18 23:04:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The war itself was like nothing previously experienced. I can't help but think though, that our WW II vets have had to deal with the same types of memories as our Vietnam Veterans. The primary difference was how our vets were recieved by John Q. Public. Opinions over our involvement may vary, and that's OK, but our gratitude toward those who served, bled and died or still suffer today shouldn't.  I remember a WW II vet sharing a war memory with me at church one day.  The memory was so powerful that he began to cry.  Do our Vietnam vets feel comfortable enough to involve themselves in this kind of open and free discussion?  Not many, I'll bet.  Thank you Vietnam Vets.  I watched you die for me on television as a child. I am forever grateful.
<p><code>-- cjsue@swbell.net  (Clifton Goins) </code><p>


